# Code Quality & Formatting Rules

## Code Style

- Use Prettier for consistent code formatting
- Write concise, technical code with accurate examples
- Use functional and declarative programming patterns
- Avoid classes; prefer functional components
- Use descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs (e.g., isLoading, hasError)

## File Structure

Structure files in this order:

1. Exported component
2. Subcomponents
3. Helper functions
4. Static content
5. Type definitions

## Naming Conventions

- Use lowercase with dashes for directories (e.g., `components/auth-wizard`)
- Favor named exports for components
- Use descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs
- Use PascalCase for component names
- Use camelCase for variables and functions

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Use interfaces over types when possible
- Avoid enums; use maps instead
- Use strict mode in TypeScript
- Define proper interfaces for component props
- Use generic types when appropriate

## Error Handling Patterns

- Handle errors at the beginning of functions
- Use early returns for error conditions
- Avoid deeply nested if statements
- Use if-return pattern instead of else statements
- Implement proper error boundaries

## Performance Guidelines

- Use useMemo and useCallback hooks appropriately
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders
- Implement code splitting for non-critical components
- Use React.Suspense for lazy loading
- Optimize images and assets

## Testing Requirements

- Write unit tests for all components
- Use descriptive test names
- Test both happy path and edge cases
- Mock external dependencies
- Maintain good test coverage

## Documentation

- Add JSDoc comments for complex functions
- Document component props with TypeScript interfaces
- Include usage examples in component documentation
- Keep README files up to date
